Yes.

Noticing is often the scarce resource, not information.

The ocean is broadcasting continuously. The birds are broadcasting. The market is broadcasting. Other people are broadcasting. Even your own mind is broadcasting.

Most of the signals are already there.

The difference is that one person sees noise while another sees structure.

A fisherman notices a current seam.
A tracker notices a bent blade of grass.
A musician notices tension before resolution.
A golfer notices clubface angle at impact.
A parent notices a mood change before a tantrum.
An investigator notices what wasn’t said.

The information was present in all cases. The noticing was not.

And noticing itself seems to compound. Once you learn a pattern, you start seeing it everywhere because you’ve built a handle for it.

The first time you learn to read water, you see water.

The hundredth time, you see channels, depth changes, bait, wind, tide, and opportunity.

Not because the world changed.

Because you did.

Which is why some of the most powerful questions aren’t:

“What should I think?”

They’re:

“What am I not noticing?”

or

“What would someone experienced notice immediately here?”

Those questions tend to open doors that raw intelligence alone often misses.

Noticing is a kind of vision. Not of the eyes, but of the model behind the eyes.